Package io.github.xrickastley.sevenelements.element

Class InternalCooldownType

java.lang.Object
io.github.xrickastley.sevenelements.element.InternalCooldownType
public final class InternalCooldownType extends Object
An InternalCooldownType is a class used for holding different types of Internal Cooldowns by having various instances of the "Reset Interval" and the "Gauge Sequence" variables.

Parameters

The id is the unique Identifier that seperates this InternalCooldownType instance from the rest. Regardless of the reset interval or gauge sequence's values; if the value for the id is different, that InternalCooldownType instance is regarded to be different from one that has the same values.

The reset interval is the amount of ticks required before the timer resets. After the timer has reset, the gauge sequence is set back to 0 and the Internal Cooldown is considered to not be active.

The gauge sequence is the amount of elemental attacks required before an element can be applied again, where the elemental attacks share ICD. When the amount of elemental attacks exceed that of the gauge sequence, the Internal Cooldown is considered to not be active, however, this does not reset the timer given by the reset interval.

Hardcoded ICD Types

An InternalCooldownType isn't validated or registered against the registry, so a "hardcoded" InternalCooldownType instance may exist. However, due to the fact that these instances aren't registered against the registry, there may be instances where two seperate InternalCooldownType instances have the same id.

Though harmless in practice, it may be confusing to have two InternalCooldownType instances at the same time. The InternalCooldownType class provides two methods you may use to create hardcoded instances of it.
  • InternalCooldownType.of() creates a purely hardcoded instance of InternalCooldownType.
  • InternalCooldownType.registered() creates a hardcoded instance of InternalCooldownType that is registered to the dynamic Internal Cooldown Type registry. This hardcoded instance is not overwritable by data-driven means.
